</article><div id="respond" class="comments-closed"><p>Comments are no longer being accepted.</p></div>
<div id="legacy-comments" class="entry-comments module">
		<div class="the-comment alt" id="comment-21283">

		<div class="comment-meta">

			<span class="comment-author">Lisa</span>
			<span class="comment-link">
				<a href="#comment-21283" title="Comment Permalink">
					<span class="comment-date">September 11, 2009</span>
					<span class="comment-middot">&middot;</span>
					<span class="comment-time">9:15 am</span>
				</a>
			</span>
		</div>
		<div class="comment-content" style="display:block;">

			<p>Having attended both a top state school and an Ivy, I can tell you that there most certainly is a difference between the two. I don&#8217;t think that most of the people who have posted comments have a grasp of the difference between kids who go to the top schools, like Harvard, and everyone else. This isn&#8217;t to say that these kids are better or worth more, but they are often much more gifted than your average &#8216;good student&#8217;. Harvard&#8217;s job isn&#8217;t to be the great equalizer; that&#8217;s what state schools are for. Harvard is out to cultivate true greatness by bringing together a cross section of the most brilliant young minds. And they happen to have a broader definition of brilliant than most of you who adhere to the SAT/grades racket; which is what makes them brilliant and leaves most of you outside it&#8217;s gates leaving messages such as these.</p>
<p>Many of the kids of parents who have been posting have probably been (or will be) hampered by the mindsets displayed here. This overemphasis on Harvard for 6 year olds will no doubt produce the kind of kid who doesn&#8217;t have true pleasures at which to excel, but who will instead spend the next dozen years cultivating some type of persona his/her parent thinks will win over the adcom. And for those who think that affirmative action is the reason their (white/male) kid didn&#8217;t get in or won&#8217;t, kids of parents who think like this are even less likely to get in. If Harvard accepted only the top students by virtue of grades and SATs, the campus would be swarming with Asians, not whites. Just look at Berkeley after the Baake case.</p>

		</div>
	</div><!-- #comment-## -->
	<div class="the-comment" id="comment-21301">

		<div class="comment-meta">

			<span class="comment-author">Shane Riorden</span>
			<span class="comment-link">
				<a href="#comment-21301" title="Comment Permalink">
					<span class="comment-date">September 11, 2009</span>
					<span class="comment-middot">&middot;</span>
					<span class="comment-time">10:17 am</span>
				</a>
			</span>
		</div>
		<div class="comment-content" style="display:block;">

			<p>No system can rationally choose &#8220;the best&#8221; 1000 applicants out of a pool of 9000 most of whom are &#8220;qualified&#8221; . Of course the admitted class is terrific by any test you can apply, but out of the same pool one could have picked  six other entering classes indistinguishable by any statistical standard you decide on. Solution: Eliminate the truly underqualified ( send them a polite letter at once)  pick a few hundred you really want for special reasons (plays the cello, star quarterback at high school, physics whiz, knows three foreign languages; etc.) Admit this group at once.  Feed all the other names into a computer program with many stated constraints to give some balance by gender, family income, race perhaps, home region, GPA, other quantifiable qualities,and total number to be offered admission. This &#8220;class&#8221; wiil be statistically indisinguishable from the one 34 deans come up with  after 1000 hours of headscratching and discussion. If this process is made transparent, no one&#8217;s ego will be bruised by being &#8220;rejected&#8221; by Harvard (Yale, Williams, Princeton etc).<br />
      I am a retired college administrator (Ivy League) of 32 year&#8217;s experience. I once made this proposal to an admissions officer.She said, &#8220;But that would take away my job.&#8221;  How true.       S. Riorden</p>

		</div>
	</div><!-- #comment-## -->
	<div class="the-comment alt" id="comment-21303">

		<div class="comment-meta">

			<span class="comment-author">SC</span>
			<span class="comment-link">
				<a href="#comment-21303" title="Comment Permalink">
					<span class="comment-date">September 11, 2009</span>
					<span class="comment-middot">&middot;</span>
					<span class="comment-time">10:55 am</span>
				</a>
			</span>
		</div>
		<div class="comment-content" style="display:block;">

			<p>It’s a vicious cycle. People want to know how to get admission into Harvard. The NY Times publishes a Q&#038;A session with a Harvard dean. More people want to know how to get admission into Harvard, and the fact that every person needs to find the best undergraduate college for him or herself is lost in the media hype. </p>
<p>I was admitted into Harvard and Princeton a number of years ago. I went to Princeton because they offered me 50% more financial aid. I also preferred Princeton’s focus on undergraduates. Harvard has better name recognition because of the success of their graduate and professional schools alumni (and faculty, I should say). </p>
<p>Some people will be more impressed with you if you went to Harvard than if you went to Princeton than if you went to Podunk, including a number of people reading this article and these comments. That’s acceptable the first few years out of college &#8211; though I’d also add that if someone is more impressed that you went to Harvard versus Princeton then that’s not someone worth impressing (Those in the know&#8230;). More importantly, if you’re 20 years out of college and the most impressive one-liner you have in your arsenal is “I went to Harvard/Princeton/Podunk” then you haven’t really done much with that opportunity.</p>
<p>Consider this study by Dale and Krueger (of the Mellon Foundation and Princeton University, respectively). Brief summary: Students accepted at “highly selective” institutions who instead went to “moderately selective” institutions had similar income levels 20 years later as the students who did attend the “highly selective” colleges. Of course, money is not the determinant of success; it is just a quantifiable component.</p>
<p><a href="http://www.brookings.edu/articles/2004/10education_easterbrook.aspx" rel="nofollow">http://www.brookings.edu/articles/2004/10education_easterbrook.aspx</a></p>

		</div>
	</div><!-- #comment-## -->
	<div class="the-comment" id="comment-21307">

		<div class="comment-meta">

			<span class="comment-author">Will Dix</span>
			<span class="comment-link">
				<a href="#comment-21307" title="Comment Permalink">
					<span class="comment-date">September 11, 2009</span>
					<span class="comment-middot">&middot;</span>
					<span class="comment-time">11:04 am</span>
				</a>
			</span>
		</div>
		<div class="comment-content" style="display:block;">

			<p>Harvard&#8217;s admission policies and procedures are no more or less thoughtful than any other college&#8217;s that deals with applicants as individuals rather than as data. Many years in the Amherst admission office and good friendships with admission officers from many institutions all over the country tell me that those in admission struggle constantly to make the &#8220;right&#8221; decisions for their institutions and the applicants themselves. It would be best for readers to consider Bill&#8217;s comments representative of college admission and not simply about Harvard.<br />
When I read these articles and responses I&#8217;m often reminded of the blind men and the elephant&#8211;we only know the small part of the creature that we&#8217;ve had some direct experience with. Really, there are no explanations for why things go the way the do in admission that will satisfy everyone&#8211;especially at ultra-competitive places. Into that vacuum will rush all kinds of &#8220;reasons&#8221; for what happens&#8211; alumni &#038; donor spots reserved for half the class, &#8220;minority&#8221; set-asides, etc.<br />
The best way to approach the college admission process is to be Zen-like about it: focus on the now and be fully present in everything you do; that way you will have lived the full life a college expects of you. Even more important, do not focus on the target&#8211;that is the surest way to miss it. Let it go and be secure in the knowledge that you will be fine wherever you go. That&#8217;s not just blather&#8211;as a high school counselor I&#8217;ve found that the happiest kids are those who know they&#8217;ll do their best wherever they go and who do not depend on external certification to feel validated.</p>

		</div>
	</div><!-- #comment-## -->
	<div class="the-comment alt" id="comment-21309">

		<div class="comment-meta">

			<span class="comment-author">Scott</span>
			<span class="comment-link">
				<a href="#comment-21309" title="Comment Permalink">
					<span class="comment-date">September 11, 2009</span>
					<span class="comment-middot">&middot;</span>
					<span class="comment-time">11:15 am</span>
				</a>
			</span>
		</div>
		<div class="comment-content" style="display:block;">

			<p>I am a graduate of Yale (undergrad and medical) from the 60&#8217;s.  I think I got in partly on &#8220;geographic distribution&#8221; although I did have good SAT&#8217;s etc.  My family was very working class and although they had to pay a lot I did have substantial scholarship assistance.  I graduated #1 in my class and have benefitted in innumerable ways from the incredible richess of my Yale education.  All professors, BTW, no grad students ever (except supplementary discussion groups).  And I agree it is nice to name drop, although I try not to do that.</p>
<p>All this said, both of our children attended smaller excellent liberal arts colleges and their lives are just fine too, thank you very much.  Way too much is made these days of the value of an Ivy League education.  It does not make you &#8220;ruling class&#8221; any more nor does it necessarily furnish your mind any better than alternatives.  And I don&#8217;t think many companies or professional groups care any more either.  Think about it:  the professors even at junior colleges are now of such high quality a talented student can get everything they need virtually anywhere.  Even, I dare say, online.  And as for learning from others about diversity and so on, well, that is a lifelong process for all of us.</p>
<p>The &#8220;elite&#8221; schools have become so difficult to get into, especially with their current emphasis on internationalism, that students should stop worrying about it.  Try if you wish but make good backup plans and you will be very happy and very well equipped for the 21st century.</p>

		</div>
	</div><!-- #comment-## -->
