			<p>Mary Shelley&#8217;s &#8220;Frankenstein&#8221; is not nearly as scary as Harvard&#8217;s admission process, designed to construct the super-human organism called the Freshman Class.  What Harvard and other elite colleges dont get is that their hyper-competitve policies reward neurotic backstabbing cynical overarchievers and their largely affluent parents who can pay the price:  for expensive musical lessons, travel soccer, mercy missions to Africa, academic and admission tutors etc.  I&#8217;d like to hear one admission officer say it&#8217;s more impressive for a kid to get a job suitable for a teenager (lifeguard ?) and earn spending money (and learn the mundane lesson that you have to work for the things you want and live within your means) than work at an unpaid internship (that Mummy or Daddy arranged and support by giving the kid allowance $$ and a car during the year).   And Harvard&#8217;s acknowledged desire for superstars sends the message that even as a kid, there&#8217;s no time to smell the roses &#8212; you&#8217;ve never done enough, you cant relax, you cant just be a kid &#8212; it&#8217;s not enough to get straight A&#8217;s, you must take the most advanced courses in every subject whether interested or not (lacking interest itself is an academic demerit), with perfect SATS, you also must unique extra-curricilurs like playing symphonic cello in the marching band on the foot controlled non-carbon emitting platform you designed and built yourself.  From all accounts, heaven is not nearly as hard to get into as Harvard.  What&#8217;s that say about Harvard?</p>

