	<div class="the-comment" id="comment-21361">

		<div class="comment-meta">

			<span class="comment-author">Cathy M.</span>
			<span class="comment-link">
				<a href="#comment-21361" title="Comment Permalink">
					<span class="comment-date">September 11, 2009</span>
					<span class="comment-middot">&middot;</span>
					<span class="comment-time">4:36 pm</span>
				</a>
			</span>
		</div>
		<div class="comment-content" style="display:block;">

			<p>In response to A.L.B. (post #64), Evan M. (post#75), and anyone else who shares their false and insulting view of the caliber of the vast majority of legacy admits to today&#8217;s Harvard &#8230; I am appalled by your misinformed and insensitive assessment.</p>
<p>There is general agreement that at least 80-90% of the +/-29,000 applicants (using class of 2013 numbers) are actually &#8220;qualified&#8221; to attend Harvard, due to their exceptionally high grades, scores, and level of extracurricular involvement.  Therefore, it goes without saying that virtually all of the legacy candidates would be well-qualified, regardless of their legacy status.  If all else is equal, why should they be penalized because their parents attended Harvard?  In my experience, the children of over-achievers tend to be over-achievers themselves; they were raised with high standards, in an environment where educational excellence was encouraged and celebrated.  Many are minorities, athletes, and skilled artists. Why in the world shouldn&#8217;t a college accept these students?  what is wrong with wanting to continue a family&#8217;s legacy/tradition if the student in question is supremely qualified.  And yes, these students almost always are.</p>
<p>My daughter was such a student in high school.  She was a National Merit Scholar, a Cum Laude member, an AP Scholar with Distinction, etc. She also earned almost perfect SAT scores across the board (many 800&#8217;s on subject tests, etc.), and a nationally and regionally recognized singer and artist.  She worked unbelievably hard in high school, and also found time to volunteer for several organizations.  She is also a very good person, well-loved and respected by teachers and peers (ahh &#8212; there&#8217;s that elusive &#8220;character&#8221;  trait.)</p>
<p>She was accepted at every college to which she applied &#8212; Harvard, Yale, Princeton, Penn, Dartmouth, Brown, and Vanderbilt, despite the fact that she had no &#8220;connections&#8221; to any of the other schools, and was one of the thousands of white, middle-class females from New England to apply. </p>
<p>Her final decision to attend Harvard was, unfortunately, fraught with anxiety due to the very sentiments expressed by  &#8220;A.L.B &#8221; and &#8220;Evan M.&#8221; in this forum: she was afraid that everyone would think she got in because she was a legacy.  Fortunately, since matriculating, she has met a couple of other legacies whose accomplishments, skills, and talents are awe-inspiring.</p>
<p>Perhaps, in the past, some unqualified legacies were admitted. However, recently, the bar has been raised to an almost unbelievable height. With today&#8217;s plethora of exceptionally qualified applicants, including legacies, who make up the applicant pool, the opposite situation exists.  Almost all of the legacies are supremely qualified across the board &#8212; perhaps better qualified than many other candidates.  Therefore, there is absolutely no reason for the college to admit any who are not. Sadly, the majority of these exceptional students will be rejected, simply because they ARE legacies.</p>
<p>Every Harvard undergraduate has the right to be incredibly proud of him or herself.  Each has worked unbelievably hard to earn his or her spot at this elite institution, and each  truly deserves to be there.</p>

		</div>
	</div><!-- #comment-## -->
	<div class="the-comment alt" id="comment-21365">

