			</span>
		</div>
		<div class="comment-content" style="display:block;">

			<p>As the father of two Harvard legacy students from a wealthy Westchester family I’d like to make some observations and offer some advice.</p>
<p>The first is that Harvard is a private school and can shape its admissions policies however it wants.   When the government adds it to its growing collection of corporations the public’s opinion will count.   If you don’t like their policies don’t apply!  This is true of every private school; not just Harvard.</p>
<p>Don’t ever buy into the notion that wealthy legacies are inherently unworthy.   It would be easy to launch into a long essay in this regard but let me keep it short:  The vast, vast, vast majority of legacies at top schools are more than worthy of acceptance.  In most cases the suggestion that they are not is a function of ignorance or class-related angers.  It is also a tool that helps parents whose kids did not make the cut explain away their failures.</p>
<p>Always remember that every child with a college educated parent is a legacy somewhere.  Most schools have some sort of a legacy policy.  If you would like to take advantage of that reality have your kids apply to YOUR school.  Don’t begrudge HYP kids their connection.</p>
<p>Understand that the same individuals that decry the legacy hook will rapidly change their tune when they finally get a kid in.   It is these folks that will shriek the loudest when it’s time for the grandchildren to go.</p>
<p>My kids collectively hold acceptances to 19 of the most prestigious colleges in the world and both choose Harvard.  It is still the gold standard for higher education.  VERITAS.</p>

