			<p>&#8220;Let me assume that 80 to 90 percent of the students who apply to Harvard are qualified and could reasonably be expected to do well there. They have good GPA scores and SATs.&#8221; </p>
<p>I&#8217;m a Harvard alum (&#8217;86) and I&#8217;ve interviewed applicants to Harvard for more than a dozen years, one to three per year.  Three of my interviewees have been accepted.</p>
<p>Every applicant is interviewed.  There is no pre-screening of their records.  I do not think that 80 to 90 percent of applicants are &#8220;qualified and could reasonably be expected to do well.&#8221;  I&#8217;d put the number at 40 to 60 percent.  Which (a) is just my opinion and (b) is still quite high compared to the acceptance rate.  But I do think the applicant pool is not quite that strong.</p>

		</div>
	</div><!-- #comment-## -->
	<div class="the-comment" id="comment-21637">

		<div class="comment-meta">

			<span class="comment-author">David Brownell</span>
			<span class="comment-link">
				<a href="#comment-21637" title="Comment Permalink">
					<span class="comment-date">September 15, 2009</span>
					<span class="comment-middot">&middot;</span>
					<span class="comment-time">4:02 pm</span>
				</a>
			</span>
		</div>
		<div class="comment-content" style="display:block;">

			<p>This is for Amy, #88. </p>
<p>Yes, Harvard makes mistakes, both on acceptances and on rejections. I&#8217;ve interviewed applicants for 35+ years, and seen the other interview reports from my city. Every year some students who seem wonderful to us don&#8217;t get in, and their interviewers are distressed. Every now and again a student gets in who did not impress his interviewers. </p>
<p>Harvard Admissions makes no pretense to having an infallible system, and would probably admit that all they can do is make their best guess. I tell every student I interview that the final decisions in cutting the class down to fit the number of beds available are often based on imaginary distinctions, and that no one who&#8217;s rejected should say, &#8220;Oh, Harvard&#8217;s infallible. I&#8217;m not as good as so-and-so who got in.&#8221; Instead say, &#8220;Well, they made a mistake this time.&#8221;</p>
<p>No admissions office can predict everything about a student&#8217;s future. One classmate of mine developed schizophrenia freshman year and has been institutionalized since. Some classmates fell into alcoholism and other problems. Some percentage of any class will not fulfil their promise, and some students who seemed less impressive at 17 will become major contributors in their field. As a Harvard graduate, I occasionally meet other grads who depress me because they feel that having been admitted to Harvard validates them for life. It doesn&#8217;t. </p>
<p>As several people have said, there are plenty of first-rate colleges, and for some students, someplace other than Harvard may be a better fit. They will still meet wonderful classmates and graduate with a good education. One benefit of a Harvard education (I have 2 Harvard degrees) is that you learn that it doesn&#8217;t mean all that much. </p>
<p>One factor in admissions for which I do blame the schools is that too many play the yield game. One year we had a superbly qualified applicant whose parents had been undergraduates at Harvard, and then gotten graduate degrees from Harvard, making this kid a four-way legacy. But she really, really, really wanted to go to Yale. Yale rejected her. The only basis I could see for rejecting her was that they looked at her Harvard legacy status, and said, &#8220;Uh-huh. If we admit her, she&#8217;ll just go to Harvard, and that will damage our yield.&#8221; She ended up at Harvard where she did well, and is now interviewing applicants herself. </p>
<p>Amy, forget about getting turned down by Harvard. In the long run, that has as much weight as whether or not you were the top student in your 8th grade class&#8212;unless you let it be a big deal.                                             David &#8217;63</p>

		</div>
	</div><!-- #comment-## -->
